indicator: Household income is calculated using all sources of individual income including all individuals residing together who are related. Median household income means that half of all households have a higher annual income and half are lower than the median income.
When comparing county estimates confidence intervals should be used with caution because the model-based estimates result in correlated percentages.
Source for household income data: 2019 American Community Survey.

Poverty is defined here by comparing a household's annual income to a set of federal poverty thresholds as determined by the U.S. Census Bureau. In 2019 for example a two adult two child household below the 100% poverty threshold had an annual income below $25926 below the 185% poverty threshold if less than $47963 in annual income and below the 200% poverty threshold if less than $51853 in annual income for a two adult two child household. Return to http://health.mn.gov/mndatapoverty to learn more.
